<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>a: [The Council and the People by a decision ] and a [decree} honoured [Marcus] Aurelius [Zen]on, son of Publius Celtius Zenon, the son of Dionysios, with the [finest] and greatest honours - a man of the well-born among us, one whose life style has benn and is seemly and worthy of respect to the point of being a demonstration of virtue; and [?on becoming a ] town councillor [?he instituted a fund for distributions of money [ . . .</p><p>b: The appointed day for the lottery is the 20th day of the fifth month.</p>
</div>
<div n="notyet" type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>The opening was apparently more formal than is often the case, probably referring to decisions of the Council (δόξαντα) and decrees of the people (ψηφίσματα).</p><p>The honorand's name suggests that he took <term lang="la">praenomen</term> and <term lang="la">nomen</term> as a result of Caracalla's Edict of Citizenship in 212 A.D., but, here at least, dropped the different <term lang="la">praenomen</term> and <term lang="la">nomen</term> of his father. M. Aurelius Zenon is praised in terms commonly used for those who dies young before holding many - or any - public offices; χρώμενον, in l.14-15 however implies that he is still alive, so we cannot fill line 18 with [καὶ τἐλευτήσαντα; perhaps then with [καὶ βοὐλευτἣν γενόμενον.</p><p>The formula in text b implies that he gave a sum of money for annual division among a lot-selected group (probably of town-councillors), so εις αἰωνίους κλήρουσ (vel. sim.) a procedure which is recorded in several other texts (see word index).</p>
                                                   </div>
